\begin_layout Subsection
Theoretical Model
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Theoretic-Model"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider an environment with a two-tiered production network.
 Downstream firms, indexed by 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, sell differentiated varieties to consumers.
 Upstream firms, indexed by 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, sell inputs used in production by the downstream firms.
 Firms, both upstream and downstream, will be able to alter their productivity
 through their choice of R&D, represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{I}$
\end_inset

, or production structure, represented by 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\omega}$
\end_inset

.
 Aggregate R&D, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{I}}$
\end_inset

, and aggregate network structure, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\Omega}$
\end_inset

, will depend on firm-level choices and additionally influence production
 technology.
 Factor prices are determined by a freely-traded outside good.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
I interpret the model results as characterizing optimal policy for one sector,
 sufficiently small that outcome on this sector do not affect economy-wide
 aggregates like factor prices or preferences.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Technology.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I specify technology in terms of a upstream and downstream firm's  cost
 of production:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{alignedat}{2}\text{c_{f,j}\Bigl(\boldsymbol{I}_{f},\boldsymbol{\omega}_{f},\boldsymbol{\mathcal{I}},\boldsymbol{\Omega}\Bigr)} & \text{ and } & c_{j}\Bigl(\boldsymbol{\bar{p}}_{j,I},\boldsymbol{I}_{j},\boldsymbol{\omega}_{j},\boldsymbol{\mathcal{I}},\boldsymbol{\Omega}\Bigr)\end{alignedat}
.
\]

\end_inset

Each firm can affect productivity through R&D expenditures 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\boldsymbol{I}_{j},\boldsymbol{I}_{f}\}$
\end_inset

 - potentially along a number of input-specific, buyer-specific, or country-spec
ific dimensions.
 Each firm chooses a production structure that alters costs, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\boldsymbol{\omega}_{j},\boldsymbol{\omega}_{f}\}$
\end_inset

.
 As an example, this may represent locations decisions - both the choice
 of where to produce and where to do R&D - or firm-to-firm linkages made
 between suppliers and buyers.
 Downstream costs additionally depend on a vector of input prices, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\bar{p}}_{j,I}=\{\bar{p}_{f,j}\}_{f}$
\end_inset

, provided by upstream firms.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The dependence of costs on factor prices is suppressed into the choice of
 production structure 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{j},\omega_{f}$
\end_inset

.
 For instance, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 may denote the location of production.
 If locations vary only in the cost of labor, differences in cost under
 various values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 simply reflects difference in wages.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The aggregates state - which includes moments of R&D expenditure, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{I}}$
\end_inset

, and industry structure, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\Omega}$
\end_inset

 - additionally affect costs.
 The state variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{I}}$
\end_inset

 represents a standard form of Marshallian externalities from collective
 knowledge production, while aggregate industry 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\Omega}$
\end_inset

 structure capture other forms of spillovers like geographic agglomeration
 forces.
 These aggregates can be multi-dimensional and depend differently on the
 components of R&D and production structure.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For example, there may be country-specific aggregate R&D levels that depend
 only on R&D spending done in those countries.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Policy.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A planner will have the opportunity to affect the prices and costs enter
 the firms' problems.
 In particular, I write final prices 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\bar{p}_{j}\}$
\end_inset

, input prices 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\bar{p}_{f,j}\}$
\end_inset

, and R&D costs 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\bar{r}_{j,k},\bar{r}_{f,l}\}$
\end_inset

 as a function of the underlying variables and policy wedges: 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{alignedat}{2}\text{Final Price:} & \quad & \bar{p}_{j}= & \left(1-t_{j}\right)p_{j},\\
\text{Input Prices:} & \quad & \bar{p}_{f,j}= & \left(1-t_{f}\right)\left(1-t_{f,j}\right)p_{f,j},\\
\text{Downstream R\&D Cost:} & \quad & \bar{r}_{j,k}= & \left(1-s_{j,k}\right)r,\\
\text{Upstream R\&D Cost:} & \quad & \bar{r}_{f,k}= & \left(1-s_{f,k}\right)r.
\end{alignedat}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{alignedat}{1}\bar{p}_{j}= & \left(1-t_{j}\right)p_{j},\\
\bar{p}_{f,j}= & \left(1-t_{f}\right)\left(1-t_{f,j}\right)p_{f,j},\\
\bar{r}_{j,k}= & \left(1-s_{j,k}\right)r,\\
\bar{r}_{f,l}= & \left(1-s_{f,l}\right)r.
\end{alignedat}
\]

\end_inset

The indices 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\ell$
\end_inset

 are for each separate dimension of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{I}_{j}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{I}_{f}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For example, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{I}_{j}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{I}_{f}$
\end_inset

 may consist of location-specific R&D components that differentially affect
 cost according to xxx.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 In addition, I assume that the cost of a particular production structure
 takes the following form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bar{f}\left(\omega_{f}\right)=f\left(\omega_{f}\right)+\phi\left(\omega_{f}\right)\text{ and }\bar{f}\left(\omega_{j}\right)=f\left(\omega_{j}\right)+\phi\left(\omega_{j}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\phi^{U}(\omega_{j}),\phi^{D}(\omega_{j})\}$
\end_inset

is a tax/subsidy associated with production structure 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Profit Maximization.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Downstream firms determine final prices, R&D expenditures, and firm structure
 to maximize profits:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\pi_{j}=\max_{\bar{p}_{j},\boldsymbol{I}_{j},\omega_{j}}q_{j}\left(p_{j}\right)\left(\bar{p}_{j}-c_{j}\left(\boldsymbol{\bar{p}}_{j,I},\boldsymbol{I_{j}},\omega_{j},\boldsymbol{\mathcal{I}},\boldsymbol{\Omega}\right)\right)-\boldsymbol{\bar{r}}_{j}\boldsymbol{I}_{j}-\bar{f}\left(\omega_{j}\right).\label{eq: Downstream Profits}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Downstream firms each face a residual demand curve and wield some monopoly
 power.
 I assume that R&D resources are in perfectly elastic supply at a cost 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\bar{r}}_{j}$
\end_inset

 to the firm.
 Finally, each production structure is associated with fixed cost payment.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Likewise, upstream firms face a similar profit maximization problem:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\pi_{f}=\max_{\left\{ \bar{p}_{f,j}\right\} _{j},\boldsymbol{I}_{f},\omega_{f}}\sum_{j}q_{f,j}\left(p_{f,j}\right)\left[\bar{p}_{f,j}-c_{f,j}\Bigl(\boldsymbol{I}_{f},\omega_{f},\boldsymbol{\mathcal{I}},\boldsymbol{\Omega}\Bigr)\right]-\boldsymbol{\bar{r}}_{f}\boldsymbol{I}_{f}-\bar{f}\left(\omega_{f}\right)\label{eq: Upstream Profits}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the substantive difference of note is that profits come from the sum
 of sales across all buyers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Aggregate State.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The firm-level choices of R&D expenditure 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\boldsymbol{I}_{f},\boldsymbol{I}_{j}\}$
\end_inset

 and structure 
\begin_inset Formula $\{\omega_{f},\omega_{j}\}$
\end_inset

 determine the aggregate R&D levels and industry structure.
 And these aggregate can be multi-dimensional functions of the firms' choices:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\mathcal{I}}=\boldsymbol{\mathcal{I}}\left(\{\boldsymbol{I}_{f},\boldsymbol{I}_{j}\}\right)\text{ and }\boldsymbol{\Omega}=\boldsymbol{\Omega}\left(\{\omega_{f},\omega_{j}\}\right).\label{eq: Aggregation}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
[X] What if 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\mathcal{I}}=\boldsymbol{\mathcal{I}}\left(\{\boldsymbol{I}_{f},\boldsymbol{I}_{j}\},\left\{ \omega_{f},\omega_{j}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

? So the local R&D spillovers are directly effects by production structure?
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Utility Maximization.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
I assume that the industry modeled here is small relative to the rest of
 the economy such that utility can be represented by a quasi-linear utility
 function.
 XXX Drop In particular, a representative agent solves
\end_layout

\end_inset

A representative agent chooses an optimal consumption profile over the varieties
 produces by downstream firms and an outside good 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U=\max_{C,\left\{ c_{j}\right\} _{j}}u\left(C,\left\{ c_{j}\right\} _{j}\right)\label{eq: Utility}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

subject to 
\begin_inset Formula $C+\sum p_{j}c_{j}\leq\boldsymbol{w}\boldsymbol{L}^{\prime}+\sum_{f}\pi_{f}+\sum_{j}\pi_{j}+T.$
\end_inset

 I set as numeraire the price of the outside good 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

, use 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{w}\boldsymbol{L}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 to denote the total payments received by factors (including payments for
 R&D and entry), and 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 to denote the net government revenue from taxes and subsidies.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Equilibrium.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An equilibrium is defined by a set of prices, R&D investments, and production
 structures that solve 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: Downstream Profits"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: Upstream Profits"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: Utility"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 - subject to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: Aggregation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 as well as standard market clearing and budget constraints.
 Note, this model may admits the possibility of multiple equilibria depending
 on the extent of complementarities in R&D and network spillovers.
 Policy has the opportunity to improve outcomes either by fixing allocations
 within a given equilibrium, or by directing firms towards selecting an
 equilibrium with higher aggregate welfare.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Optimal Policy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A planner's objective is to choose a set of policy instruments, 
\begin_inset Formula $\{t_{j},t_{f},t_{f,j},s_{j,k},s_{f,l},\phi(\omega_{f}),\phi(\omega_{j})\}$
\end_inset

, that maximize welfare according to 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: Utility"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 I characterize some features of the optimal industry policy
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:Optimal-Tax-1"

\end_inset

Assume the choice of production structure is fixed.
 A planner chooses a standard set of taxes on final production and supplier
 production that corrects the monopoly distortion.
 They choose a set of taxes on the purchase of inputs that satisfies
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1-t_{f,j}=\frac{q_{j}}{q_{f,j}}\frac{\partial c_{j}}{\partial p_{f,j}}
\]

\end_inset

and they choose an R&D subsidy that satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
s_{f}=\sum_{j}\frac{\partial c_{j}}{\partial\boldsymbol{\mathcal{I}}}\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{\mathcal{I}}}{\partial\boldsymbol{I}_{f}}q_{j}+\sum_{f,j}\frac{\partial c_{f,j}}{\partial\boldsymbol{\mathcal{I}}}\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{\mathcal{I}}}{\partial\boldsymbol{I}_{f}}q_{f,j}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first tax corrects the extent to which upstream firms do not fully internali
zes the benefits of price-reductions to downstream firms.
 If Shephard's lemma held for the cost function implied by 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: Downstream Profits"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, then the first tax would not be necessary.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

