\begin_layout Plain Layout
The classic Murphy-Shleifer-Vishny (1989) big-push model shows that coordinated
 subsidies can achieve an equilibrium switch that firm-by-firm Pigouvian
 corrections cannot.
 Your model is richer: the network structure means the multiplier on coordinated
 investment depends on which links are central, not just how many firms
 are subsidized.
 A proposition here would characterize the minimum coalition of firms whose
 simultaneous subsidization triggers a switch to the high-R&D equilibrium
 — essentially, the "tipping network." This would be the first such result
 in a supply chain context with endogenous R&D and would directly motivate
 the paper's policy results: standard Pigouvian corrections are within-equilibri
um; the paper's industrial policy framework is needed precisely when you
 want to select across equilibria.
