\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lem:Optimal-Contract"

\end_inset

The optimal contract offered by a buyer agrees to purchase inputs at a fixed
 markup
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mu_{f,j}=1+2\rho\alpha,
\]

\end_inset

or, in terms of the optimal price level, a cost-plus contract
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{f,j}=\text{Unit Cost}+\alpha\times\frac{\text{R\&D Costs}}{\text{Quantities}}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The optimal contract is a cost-plus contract that reimburses the suppliers
 for a multiple 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 of their R&D investments.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
I interpret 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 as reduced-form parameter that captures the bargaining power of suppliers.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is higher, suppliers can demand greater returns to their R&D investments.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The contracted markup is increasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

.
 When the returns to R&D are high, OEMs allow suppliers to receive greater
 profits and this incentivize innovation.
 Additionally, final prices 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{j}$
\end_inset

, will be a standard CES markup over marginal costs.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, to characterize the R&D allocations, it will be useful to define R&D
 productivity indices.
 These indices come from solving out the optimal R&D allocation across countries
, allowing us to compactly write other allocation results.
 For example, with supplier's generic R&D, we use 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Upstream-R&D"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 to write
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\bar{\zeta}_{f}=\left(\sum_{c\in C_{f}}\left[\zeta_{f,c}\mathcal{I}_{c}^{\omega}d_{f,c}^{\tau_{f}}r_{c}^{-\zeta}\right]^{\frac{\varsigma}{1-\varsigma}}\right)^{\frac{1-\varsigma}{\varsigma}}.\label{eq:Productivity-Index}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

This index embeds the optimal allocation of R&D across countries, and effectivel
y summarizes the marginal cost of raising the level of 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{f}$
\end_inset

.
 Appendix Section X characterizes an equivalent index for specialized R&D
 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\zeta}_{f,j}$
\end_inset

 and OEM's R&D 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\zeta}_{j,I},\bar{\zeta}_{j,A}$
\end_inset

 using the expressions in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Downstream-R&D"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Upstream-R&D"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 With this notation defined, I present the following allocation results:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop: Suppliers R&D Allocation-1"

\end_inset

Upstream firms allocate their R&D across generic and specialized R&D, and
 within specialized R&D, as follows: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{I_{f}}{\bar{\zeta}_{f}}=\sum_{j}\frac{I_{f,j}}{\bar{\zeta}_{f,j}}\text{ and }\frac{I_{f,j}}{\sum I_{f,j}}=\frac{\left(\bar{\zeta}_{f,j}q_{f,j}\bar{c}_{f,j}\right)^{\frac{1}{1+\rho}}}{\sum_{j}\left(\bar{\zeta}_{f,j}q_{f,j}\bar{c}_{f,j}\right)^{\frac{1}{1+\rho}}}.
\]

\end_inset

Downstream firms allocate their R&D across components of production according
 to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{I_{j,I}}{I_{j,A}+I_{j,I}}=\frac{\left(\bar{\zeta}_{j,I}p_{j,I}\right)^{\frac{1}{1+\eta}}}{\left(\bar{\zeta}_{j,A}\bar{c}_{j,A}\right)^{\frac{1}{1+\eta}}+\left(\bar{\zeta}_{j,I}p_{j,I}\right)^{\frac{1}{1+\eta}}}
\]

\end_inset

An upstream firms allocates generic R&D expenditures across countries according
 to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{I_{f,c}}{\sum_{c'}I_{f,c'}}=\frac{\left(I_{f,c}\zeta_{f,c}\mathcal{I}_{c}^{\omega}d_{f,c}^{\tau_{f}}r_{c}^{-1}\right)^{\frac{\varsigma}{1-\varsigma}}}{\sum_{c'}\left(I_{f,c'}\zeta_{f,c'}\mathcal{I}_{c'}^{\omega}d_{f,c'}^{\tau_{f}}r_{c'}^{-1}\right)^{\frac{\varsigma}{1-\varsigma}}}
\]

\end_inset

with an equivalent expression for specialized R&D 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{f,j,c}$
\end_inset

 and OEM's allocations 
\begin_inset Formula $I_{j,I,c},I_{j,A,c}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This characterization highlights four economic forces.
 First, the division between generic and specialized R&D reflects their
 relative productivity and returns.
 When generic R&D is highly productive (high 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\zeta}_{f}$
\end_inset

), suppliers tilt investment towards cost reductions that benefits all buyers.
 When buyer-specific productivity is high, specialized R&D becomes more
 attractive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second, specialized R&D is allocated towards buyers for which suppliers
 are productive 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\zeta}_{f,j}$
\end_inset

, have high quantity 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{f,j}$
\end_inset

, and have high cost 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{c}_{f,j}$
\end_inset

.
 Higher quantities increase the scale over which cost-reducing innovations
 apply, and higher cost increase the marginal benefit of innovation.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
In equilibrium, higher costs will also reduce the quantities that suppliers
 receive.
 Both through competition in input markets, and reduced input purchase from
 downstream firms.
 The equilibrium implications of cost shocks should therefore not be interpreted
 as shocks that necessarily increase innovation.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 When the elasticity 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 increases, the returns to R&D become stronger ad more uniform across buyers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Third, OEMs allocate R&D towards the components of production where productivity
 improvements have the highest return - either due to high R&D productivity
 (
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\zeta}_{j,I},\bar{\zeta}_{j,A}$
\end_inset

) or high production costs (
\begin_inset Formula $p_{j,I},$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\bar{c}_{j,A}$
\end_inset

).
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This result hinges on the assumption that inputs are complements.
 If inputs were sufficiently substitutable, it would be the case that more
 R&D would be allocated to the components of production that had the lowest
 cost.
 The data supports the fact that inputs are complements.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Fourth, the cross-country allocation of R&D reflects a standard CES tradeoff
 between productivity and cost.
 R&D flows to locations where productivity is high relative to costs.
 And as 
\begin_inset Formula $\varsigma\rightarrow1$
\end_inset

, expenditure concentrates in the single most productive location.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
This theory suggests why directly interpreting reduced-form coefficients
 from innovation outcomes as causal coefficients, even when using instruments,
 is problematic.
 As R&D will endogenously be allocated to the locations where it is most
 productive.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Despite the fact that inputs are specified as perfect complements in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Downstream-Costs"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, unit costs will not be additive in the cost of assembly and inputs since
 the endogenous allocation of R&D allows firms to reduce their dependence
 on the expensive component of production.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Do I characterize prices? 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Newpage pagebreak
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Equilibrium Comparative Statics - First Order
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Comparative-Statics-First-Order"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To get a better sense of the model mechanism and the potential implications
 of policy, I characterize the response of industry outcomes GDP to price
 and R&D efficiency shocks.
 But changes in prices and R&D efficiency depend on more primitive parameters,
 and hence we provide some results to think about how prices respond to
 cost shocks (which affect productivity by raising unit costs) and R&D productiv
ity shocks (which affect the efficiency of R&D investment).
 Throughout, these comparative statics allow R&D allocations and prices
 to adjust, but treat 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{f},\omega_{j}$
\end_inset

 as exogenous variables from Stage 1.
\end_layout

