\begin_layout Standard
I start by noting that changes in real output in this industry can be characteri
zed by the following comparative static:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:GDP-Response"

\end_inset

The first-order change in real industry output is given by
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d\log\text{GDP}=-\sum_{j}\Lambda_{j}d\log p_{j}=-\sum_{j}\Lambda_{j}\left(\lambda_{j,A}\left(d\log\bar{c}_{j,A}-\eta\bar{\zeta}_{j,A}\right)+\lambda_{j,I}\left(d\log p_{j,I}-\eta\bar{\zeta}_{j,I}\right)\right),
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda_{j}$
\end_inset

 measure the share of firm 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 in final expenditure, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{j,A},\lambda_{j,I}$
\end_inset

 measure the share of assembly and inputs in the cost of firm 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Changes in real output arise from either changes in productivity, manifesting
 as changes in assembly costs 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{c}_{j,A}$
\end_inset

 or input prices 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{j,I}$
\end_inset

, or changes in R&D efficiency, represented by changes in the indices 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\zeta}_{j,I}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\zeta}_{j,A}$
\end_inset

.
 While assembly costs are a technological parameter, inputs prices and productiv
ity indices are endogenous through either individual R&D choices or aggregate
 R&D spillovers.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Assembly costs are a technological parameter as we have conditioned on the
 Stage 1 choices.
 In principle, these too are endogenous to the plant location and market
 entry choices of firms.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The following results characterize the response of each to primitive cost
 or R&D productivity shocks.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The previous propositions provided characterizations of marginal price changes
 with respect to endogenous variables: 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{j,I}$
\end_inset

 (inputs prices) in Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop: Downstream Innovation Allocation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{f,j}$
\end_inset

 (upstream profit shifters) in Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop: Upstream Innovation Allocation"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 Now I offer a complete characterization of the price response to changes
 in exogenous component of input costs 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{c}_{f,j}$
\end_inset

 and assembly costs 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{j,A}.$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We ask 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\log p_{f,j}}{d\log\bar{c}_{f,j}}=-\delta_{1}\sum_{j}\left(\Lambda_{j}\lambda_{j,I}\right)\frac{d\log P_{j}}{d\log\bar{c}_{f,j}}+\delta_{2}\left((\theta-1)+\tilde{\lambda}_{j,I}\frac{d\log P_{j}}{d\log\bar{c}_{f,j}}\right)+\delta_{3}\sum_{j}\lambda_{f,j}\left((\theta-1)+\tilde{\lambda}_{j,I}\frac{d\log P_{j}}{d\log\bar{c}_{f,j}}\right)
\]

\end_inset

Now we ask 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d^{2}\log p_{f,j}}{d\log\bar{c}_{f,j}d\log\bar{c}_{f,k}}=-\delta_{1}\sum_{j}\left(\frac{d\log\Lambda_{j}}{d\log\bar{c}_{f,k}}\lambda_{j,I}+\frac{d\log\lambda_{j,I}}{d\log\bar{c}_{f,k}}\Lambda_{j}\right)\frac{d\log P_{j}}{d\log\bar{c}_{f,j}}+\delta_{2}\frac{d\log\tilde{\lambda}_{j,I}}{d\log\bar{c}_{f,k}}\frac{d\log P_{j}}{d\log\bar{c}_{f,j}}+\delta_{3}\sum_{j}\frac{d\log\lambda_{f,j}}{d\log\bar{c}_{f,k}}\left((\theta-1)+\tilde{\lambda}_{j,I}\frac{d\log P_{j}}{d\log\bar{c}_{f,j}}\right)+\delta_{3}\sum_{j}\lambda_{f,j}\frac{d\log\tilde{\lambda}_{j,I}}{d\log\bar{c}_{f,k}}\frac{d\log P_{j}}{d\log\bar{c}_{f,j}}
\]

\end_inset

Then we start to derive? So we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Lambda_{j}=\frac{P_{j}}{\sum P_{j}}
\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda_{j,I}=\frac{\bar{c}_{j,I}}{\bar{c}_{j,I}+\bar{c}_{j,A}}=\frac{P_{j}}{P_{j}+c_{j,A}}
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\lambda_{f,j}=\frac{\left(y_{f,j}\right)^{\frac{1}{1-\rho\left(\theta-1\right)}}}{\sum_{j}\left(y_{f,j}\right)^{\frac{1}{1-\rho\left(\theta-1\right)}}}
\]

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d\log P_{j}=\sum\lambda_{j,f}d\log p_{f,j}
\]

\end_inset

So we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\log\Lambda_{j}}{d\log\bar{c}_{f,k}}=\frac{d\log P_{j}}{d\log\bar{c}_{f,k}}-\sum\Lambda_{j}\frac{d\log P_{j}}{d\log\bar{c}_{f,k}}
\]

\end_inset

and we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\log\lambda_{j,I}}{d\log\bar{c}_{f,k}}=d\log P_{j}-\lambda_{j,I}P_{j}
\]

\end_inset

and we have
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
XXx A partial version of hulten's theorm, but need to acknowledge that input
 prices are endogenous, and productivity is endogenous 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop: Network Response"

\end_inset

The response of input prices to a set of buyer-supplier cost shocks 
\begin_inset Formula $d\log\bar{c}_{f,j}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d\log p_{f,j}=d\log\bar{c}_{f,j}-\sum_{k}\left(\delta_{2}\mathbb{1}_{j=k}+\delta_{3}\lambda_{f,k}\right)\left((1-\theta)d\log\bar{c}_{f,k}+\tilde{\lambda}_{j,I}d\log p_{k,I}\right)-\delta_{1}\sum_{k}\Lambda_{k}\lambda_{k,I}d\log p_{k,I}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $d\log p_{k,I}=\sum\lambda_{k,f}d\log p_{f,k}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The variables 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda_{j}$
\end_inset

 measure the share of firm 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 in final expenditure, 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{j,A},\lambda_{j,I}$
\end_inset

 measure the share of assembly and inputs in the cost of firm 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\end_inset

The variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{f,j}$
\end_inset

 is the share of downstream firm j in upstream firm f's revenue, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{j,f}$
\end_inset

 is the share of upstream firm 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 in the input price of downstream firm 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
 The variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{1}_{j=k}$
\end_inset

 is an indicator that takes a value of 1 when buyer 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 in the summand equals buyer 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
XXX I can add the market expansion thing easily.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 The parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{2}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{3}$
\end_inset

are defined below.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This comparative static reflects several forces.
 First, there is the direct effect of costs to prices, which ignoring any
 adjustments in quantity or R&D, directly pass through due to the pricing
 implications of Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem:Optimal-Contract"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second, for every buyer in a supplier's network, there is a potential supplier-s
pecific cost shock 
\begin_inset Formula $d\log\bar{c}_{f,k}$
\end_inset

, which affects R&D incentives as it increases costs and lowers demand (hence
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $1-\theta$
\end_inset

).
 And, each buyer is also experience a change in its total input costs 
\begin_inset Formula $d\log p_{k,I}$
\end_inset

, arising from changes in the prices offered by each supplier.
 Total input costs affect the R&D incentives of suppliers through four separate
 mechanisms: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\tilde{\lambda}_{j,I}\equiv\underbrace{\theta-1\frac{}{\vphantom{\left(\right)}}}_{\text{Upstream Competition}}+\underbrace{1\vphantom{\frac{}{\vphantom{\left(\right)}}}}_{\text{Input Expenditure}}-\underbrace{\frac{\rho}{\rho+1\vphantom{\left(\right)}}}_{\text{Input R\&D}}-\underbrace{\frac{1}{\rho+1}\frac{\sigma}{1+\rho\left(1-\sigma\right)}\lambda_{j,I}}_{\text{Downstream Demand}}.
\]

\end_inset

Higher input prices faced by buyer 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, benefit each supplier as it perceives weaker perceive competition and
 higher input expenditure.
 However, higher input prices lead downstream firms to reallocate R&D towards
 inputs and raise final prices, which both lower input demand.
 The resulting changes in R&D affect costs through though the reallocation
 of specialized R&D, which affects particular buyers, and expansion of generic
 R&D spending as well as the overall R&D budget, which benefits all buyers:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta_{2}\mathbb{1}_{j=k}+\delta_{3}\lambda_{f,k}=\underbrace{\frac{\rho}{1+\rho\left(1-\theta\right)}}_{\text{Reallocation of R\&D to \ensuremath{j}}}\times\mathbb{1}_{j=k}+\biggl(\underbrace{\frac{2\rho}{1-2\rho\left(\theta-1\right)}}_{\text{Generic R\&D and R\&D Budget}}-\underbrace{\frac{\rho}{1-\rho\left(\theta-1\right)}}_{\text{Reallocation of R\&D to \ensuremath{k}}}\biggr)\times\lambda_{f,k}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The final term normalizes changes in 
\begin_inset Formula $d\log p_{k,I}$
\end_inset

 to emphasize that relative prices changes are what determines reallocation
 in downstream demand: 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{1}=\left(\delta_{2}+\delta_{3}\right)\left(\sigma-1\right)/1+\rho\left(1-\sigma\right)$
\end_inset

.
 But notably, this last term will not cancel out the other 
\begin_inset Formula $d\log p_{k,I}$
\end_inset

 terms since even if every firm experienced the same cost shock such that
 relative quantities did not change, the absolute level of demand would
 change which would affect the R&D incentives of firms.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
which captures how a change in the aggregate price index, 
\begin_inset Formula $d\log D=\sum_{j}\Lambda_{j}\lambda_{j,I}d\log P_{j}$
\end_inset

, makes any individual firm 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 perceive weaker competition, and hence raises their input demand.
 What will matter is both the relative price of each downstream firm to
 the price index, and the absolute level of prices of each firm.
 These relative price changes determine which downstream firms have larger
 quantities, and hence receive more directed R&D from suppliers.
 And the absolute level of prices determines the number of units demanded,
 which in turn shapes input demand and upstream R&D incentives.
 And here, note how 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
