\begin_layout Subsection
Equilibrium Comparative Statics - Second-Order
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The final result we provide in this section is a characterization of the
 second-order effect of cost shocks.
 To parse these results, I first introduce some notation.
 First, we use Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop: Network Response"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 to characterize the first-order price response to cost changes, which we
 compactly represent as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\psi_{f,k}^{j}=d\log P_{j}/d\log c_{f,k}.
\]

\end_inset

Second, we introduce two notions of covariance in the first-order price
 response.
 The first of these,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Cov_{\Lambda}\left(\lambda_{j,I}\psi_{f,j}^{j},\lambda_{j,I}\psi_{f,k}^{j}\right)=\sum_{j}\Lambda_{j}\lambda_{j,I}\psi_{f,k}^{j}\lambda_{j,I}\psi_{f,j}^{j}-\sum_{j}\Lambda_{j}\lambda_{j,I}\psi_{f,j}^{j}\sum_{k}\lambda_{k,I}\Lambda_{k}\psi_{f,k}^{j},
\]

\end_inset

measures the covariance in prices changes experienced by downstream buyers,
 where we use the distribution of buyers in the downstream price index 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 The second of these,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Cov_{\lambda_{f}}\left(\tilde{\lambda}_{j,I}\psi_{f,j}^{j},\tilde{\lambda}_{j,I}\psi_{f,k}^{j}\right)=\sum_{j}\lambda_{f,j}\tilde{\lambda}_{j,I}\psi_{f,j}^{j}\tilde{\lambda}_{j,I}\psi_{f,k}^{j}-\sum_{j}\lambda_{f,j}\tilde{\lambda}_{j,I}\psi_{f,j}^{j}\sum_{k}\lambda_{f,k}\tilde{\lambda}_{k,I}\psi_{f,k}^{l}.
\]

\end_inset

again measures the covariance in prices changes experienced by downstream
 buyers, but instead uses the distribution of buyers in the profits of supplier
 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

.
 Using these definitions.
 We can now characterize the response of second-order effect of cost shocks
 on input prices.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop: Network Response - Second Order-1"

\end_inset

The second-order response of input prices to a set of buyer-supplier cost
 shocks {
\begin_inset Formula $d\log\bar{c}_{f,j}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $d\log\bar{c}_{f,k}$
\end_inset

} where 
\begin_inset Formula $j\neq k$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{alignedat}{1} & \frac{d^{2}\log p_{f,j}}{d\log\bar{c}_{f,j}d\log\bar{c}_{f,k}}=\delta_{1}\delta_{6}Cov_{\Lambda}\left(\lambda_{j,I}\psi_{f,j}^{j},\lambda_{j,I}\psi_{f,k}^{j}\right)+\delta_{1}\delta_{7}\sum_{j}\left(\left(1-\lambda_{j,I}\right)\psi_{f,k}^{j}\right)\lambda_{j,I}\Lambda_{j}\psi_{f,j}^{j}\\
 & \quad+\delta_{2}\delta_{8}\left(1-\lambda_{j,I}\right)\psi_{f,k}^{j}\psi_{f,j}^{j}+\delta_{3}\delta_{8}\sum_{j}\lambda_{f,j}\left(1-\lambda_{j,I}\right)\psi_{f,k}^{j}\psi_{f,j}^{j}-\delta_{3}\delta_{5}Cov_{\lambda_{f}}\left(\tilde{\lambda}_{j,I}\psi_{f,j}^{j},\tilde{\lambda}_{j,I}\psi_{f,k}^{j}\right)
\end{alignedat}
.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{alignedat}{1}\frac{d^{2}\log p_{f,j}}{d\log\bar{c}_{f,k}}= & \delta_{8}\sum_{k}\left(\delta_{2}\mathbb{1}_{j=k}+\delta_{3}\lambda_{f,k}\right)\lambda_{j,I}\left(1-\lambda_{j,I}\right)\psi_{f,k}^{j}\psi_{f,j}^{j}+\delta_{7}\delta_{1}\sum_{j}\Lambda_{j}\lambda_{j,I}\left(1-\lambda_{j,I}\right)\psi_{f,k}^{j}\psi_{f,j}^{j}\\
 & -\delta_{5}Cov_{\lambda_{f}}\left(\lambda_{j,I}\psi_{f,j}^{j},\lambda_{j,I}\psi_{f,k}^{j}\right)+\delta_{1}\delta_{6}Cov_{\Lambda}\left(\lambda_{j,I}\psi_{f,j}^{j},\lambda_{j,I}\psi_{f,k}^{j}\right)
\end{alignedat}
.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now to unpack this expression, we define each new parameter in turn.
 First, recall from above that 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{1}$
\end_inset

 determines how changes in the aggregate downstream price index affect the
 profit incentive for innovating for each buyer.
 With that in mind, note that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta_{6}=\frac{\sigma-1}{1+\rho\left(1-\sigma\right)},
\]

\end_inset

which is the elasticity of downstream demand shares with respect to cost
 changes.
 What this term captures is how the first-order changes in the final prices
 of downstream firms relocate quantity across buyers.
 These quantities in turn affect the demand faced by various suppliers and
 thus their incentive to do R&D.
 The covariance appears as a measure of the extent to which buyers which
 are experiencing large first-order price effects are in the second-order
 also experiencing reallocations of demand shares towards them.
 Relatedly, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{7}=1/\left(1+\rho\right),$
\end_inset

 which captures how for each downstream firm in the final price index, the
 cost share of inputs is changing - and hence the ability of upstream R&D
 to influence downstream prices.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{3}$
\end_inset

 determine how changes in the input prices of various buyers affects the
 R&D incentives of suppliers either through a competition effect or a reallocati
on/expansion of input demand.
 Now note,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta_{4,j}=\frac{1}{\rho+1},
\]

\end_inset

which similar to 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{7}$
\end_inset

, captures how within each buyer 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 the share of costs that is determined by upstream R&D choice is changing,
 and this amplifies any first-order feedback effect between upstream R&D
 and demand for inputs.
 The first component of 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta_{4,j}$
\end_inset

 captures how this second-order effect does not alter the competition effect
 from the change in input prices which is governed by 
\begin_inset Formula $-\theta$
\end_inset

; it only influences the input demand expansion channel 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{\rho+1}\frac{\sigma}{1+\rho\left(1-\sigma\right)}\lambda_{j,I}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, we have another change stemming from the common component of upstream
 R&D, where we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\delta_{5}=\frac{1}{1-\rho\left(\theta-1\right)},
\]

\end_inset

which is the elasticity of profit shares 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{f,j}$
\end_inset

 with respect to profit shifters 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{j}.$
\end_inset

 And why this appears with a covariance term is to measure the extent to
 which buyers which are experiencing large first-order price effects are
 in the second-order also experiencing reallocations of profits shares in
 supplier 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 toward them.
\end_layout

