\begin_layout Section
Symmetric Industry Equilibrium
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The previous section highlighted how the structure of a production network
 generates a dependence between the R&D choices of firms vertically linked
 as suppliers and buyers, and those horizontally linked either through competiti
on or a shared set of suppliers.
 While the heterogeneity present in that model is key for any quantitative
 statements, one can push the theory and develop further intuition by focusing
 on a simplified case.
 In this section I characterize an industry equilibria with homogenous upstream
 and downstream firms - abstracting from any heterogeneity in technology
 or geography.
 This simplification aims to make transparent how the model parameters govern
 the response of the economy to outsourcing and offshoring shocks.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Specifically, I assume there is a homogenous mass 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 of suppliers and mass 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 of buyers, all innovating in the same location.
 Additionally, I assume that there is an entry cost for upstream and downstream
 firms that is convex in the number of entrants: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\pi_{f}^{\gamma_{f}}=Mf_{M}\quad\text{and}\quad\pi_{j}^{\gamma_{j}}=Nf_{N},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{f},\gamma_{j}\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
One can imagine a factor in fixed supply - like land in the industry cluster
 - that generates these convexities in entry.
\end_layout

\end_inset

This entry process along with a homogenous versions of the previous equations,
 completes the characterization of the industry equilibrium.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition*
A symmetry equilibrium is characterized by upstream prices and quantities
 (
\begin_inset Formula $p_{f,j},\tilde{x}_{j}$
\end_inset

), profits (
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{f},\pi_{j}$
\end_inset

), entrants (
\begin_inset Formula $M,N$
\end_inset

), and spillovers (
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

) that satisfy Appendix Equations X.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I now provide two lemmas that I draw on and follow with comparative statics
 for the industry equilibrium.
 I will only be considering comparative statics with respect to distances
 and the exogenous component of costs, which is a necessary simplification
 for these results.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lem: No Downstream Entry"

\end_inset

In a symmetric equilibrium, there is no change in the number of downstream
 firms in response to a change in production costs or distance.
 Additionally, the total R&D expenditure of downstream firms remains fixed:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d\log N=d\log\pi_{j}=d\log\left(I_{j,I}+I_{j,A}\right)=0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This result largely follows from the assumption of fixed market size and
 a fixed markup.
 If we allowed substitution with an outside sector, e.g.
 
\begin_inset Formula $D=\bar{D}P^{\sigma-1-\kappa}$
\end_inset

 through quasi-linear preference, then this would not continue to hold.
 Changes in costs would create a market expansion effect, which would result
 in room for more downstream entrants.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "lem: Upstream Profits and Prices"

\end_inset

In a symmetric equilibrium, in response to a change in production costs
 or distance, we can express the change in profits as directly related to
 the change in input prices: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(1+\left(1+\gamma_{f}\right)\lambda_{U}\frac{\omega}{\rho}\right)d\log\pi_{f}=-\frac{1}{2\rho}d\log p_{f,j}+\frac{\tau}{2\rho}d\log d_{f}+\frac{\tau}{2\rho}d\log d_{f,j},
\]

\end_inset

and in turn we can relate 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\log K}{d\log\pi_{f}}=\left(1+\gamma_{f}\right)\lambda_{U}\text{ and }\frac{d\log M}{d\log\pi_{f}}=\gamma_{f}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{U}$
\end_inset

 is the contribution of upstream firms to knowledge spillovers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This is a symmetric equilibrium version of Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop: Network Response Corollary - Distance"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The inverse elasticity of prices with respect to R&D is 
\begin_inset Formula $1/2\rho$
\end_inset

, and since profits are proportional to R&D expenditure
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
(XXX is this a common feature of these models)
\end_layout

\end_inset

, we can use changes in upstream prices as a sufficient statistic for profits
 and thus entry.
 Finally, this also lets us extrapolate to changes in the local knowledge
 stock 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 since again R&D is proportional to profits, and it is only upstream profits
 which are changing - following Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem: No Downstream Entry"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
For intuition behind this result, note that spillovers have a larger effect
 on prices than profits.
 This difference is increasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega/\rho$
\end_inset

 - i.e.
 when spillovers are stronger.
 Otherwise, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1+\gamma_{f}\right)\lambda_{U}$
\end_inset

 is the elasticity of spillovers with respect to profits, and 
\begin_inset Formula $-\left(1+\left(1+\gamma_{f}\right)\lambda_{U}\frac{\omega}{\rho}\right)^{-1}/2\rho$
\end_inset

 is elasticity of profits with respect to prices.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, I provide sufficient conditions under which an equilibrium exists
 and is unique.
 One reason we might be worried about uniqueness or existence in this model
 is the external knowledge spillovers in 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

, and issues related to the R&D coordination between upstream and downstream
 firms.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
XXX Big-push type equilibria where upstream and downstream firms have to
 collectively undertake R&D to move into a higher profit equilibrium.
 Neither has the private incentive to do it alone.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
A sufficient condition for equilibrium existence and uniqueness when 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega>0$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{2\omega}{1+2\rho}\left(\left(1+\gamma\right)\sigma_{\pi,p}\right)+\frac{2\rho}{1+2\rho}\left[-\gamma\sigma_{\pi,p}+\left(1+\frac{1}{\theta}\gamma\sigma_{\pi,p}\right)\right]<0
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{\pi,p}=1/2\rho\left(\left(1+\gamma\right)\frac{\omega}{p}+1\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Or, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega=0$
\end_inset

, we then have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\underbrace{\frac{-\gamma}{2\rho}}_{\text{Business Stealing}}+\underbrace{\left(1+\frac{1}{\theta}\frac{\gamma}{2\rho}\right)}_{\text{Market Expansion}}<0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are several forces that work to determine equilibrium existence and
 uniqueness.
 To walk through them, imagine taking input prices to zero.
 For existence, we want to make sure the changes that occur to firm R&D
 incentives along this price path don't support an equilibrium with a price
 of zero.
 Following Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem: Upstream Profits and Prices"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, this price change is associated with higher profits, more entry, and greater
 knowledge spillovers.
 How do these changes in turn affect the R&D incentives of firms? The knowledge
 spillovers are consistent with lower prices.
 And the lower prices themselves along with the lover of variety effect
 from entry are generating higher input demand which is consistent with
 high R&D and low price.
 Existence then hinges on a business stealing effect, which has to be sufficient
ly strong such that the incentive for R&D vanishes as prices go to zero.
 A similar logic works for taking prices to infinity.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
XXX Note although these are sufficient conditions, they ought in practice
 be close to the necessary conditions.
 The proof relies on bounding an additive component by its upper bound.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Industry Planner Solution
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I start by relating the solution from the decentralized market equilibrium
 to a pseudo social-planner.
 Namely, I consider an industry planner which coordinates the investment
 of upstream and downstream firms to maximize industry profits, while facing
 an iso-elastic demand curv e with price elasticity 
\begin_inset Formula $-\sigma$
\end_inset

.
 For instance, imagine a national industry planner trying to coordinate
 behavior in an industry, hoping to win global market share whilst facing
 an elasticity of substitution across countries of 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop: Planner Solution"

\end_inset

An industry planner would choose an allocation of R&D for input technology
 across downstream and upstream firms that satisfies
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1=\frac{\sum_{f}I_{f}^{\text{Planner}}}{I_{j,I}^{\text{Planner}}},\quad\frac{\left(\theta-1\right)\left(\mu-1\right)}{\mu M^{-1/\theta}}=\frac{\sum_{f}I_{f}^{\text{Decentralized}}}{I_{j,I}^{\text{Decentralized}}}.
\]

\end_inset

And, if firms additionally differ in the exogenous component of their costs,
 a planner would allocate 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
XXX Move to another proposition XXX fix this for the more generic case
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\left(\bar{c}_{f',j}\right)^{\frac{\theta}{1-2\theta\rho}}}{\left(\bar{c}_{f,j}\right)^{\frac{\theta}{1-2\theta\rho}}}=\frac{I_{f}^{\text{Planner}}}{I_{f'}^{\text{Planner}}},\text{ and }\frac{\left(\bar{c}_{f',j}\right)^{\frac{\theta-1}{1-2\left(\theta-1\right)\rho}}}{\left(\bar{c}_{f,j}\right)^{\frac{\theta-1}{1-2\left(\theta-1\right)\rho}}}=\frac{I_{f}^{\text{Decentralized}}}{I_{f'}^{\text{Decentralized}}}
\]

\end_inset

For planner that optimizes across firms: 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{I_{j,A}^{\text{Planner}}+I_{j,I}^{\text{Planner}}}{I_{j,A}^{\text{Planner}}+I_{j,I}^{\text{Planner}}}=\frac{I_{j,A}^{\text{Decentralized}}+I_{j,I}^{\text{Decentralized}}}{I_{j,A}^{\text{Decentralized}}+I_{j,I}^{\text{Decentralized}}}=\frac{\left(\left(c_{j,A}\right)^{\frac{1}{\rho+1}}+\left(c_{j,I}\right)^{\frac{1}{\rho+1}}\right)^{\left(\rho+1\right)\left(1-\sigma\right)}}{\left(\left(c_{j,A}\right)^{\frac{1}{\rho+1}}+\left(c_{j,I}\right)^{\frac{1}{\rho+1}}\right)^{\left(\rho+1\right)\left(1-\sigma\right)}},
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
and XXX 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{I_{j,A}^{\text{Planner}}+I_{j,I}^{\text{Planner}}}{I_{j,A}^{\text{Planner}}+I_{j,I}^{\text{Planner}}}=\frac{\left(\left(c_{j,A}\right)^{\frac{1}{\rho+1}}+\left(c_{j,I}\right)^{\frac{1}{\rho+1}}\right)^{\left(\rho+1\right)\left(1-\sigma\right)}}{\left(\left(c_{j,A}\right)^{\frac{1}{\rho+1}}+\left(c_{j,I}\right)^{\frac{1}{\rho+1}}\right)^{\left(\rho+1\right)\left(1-\sigma\right)}},\text{ and }\frac{I_{j,A}^{\text{Decentralized}}+I_{j,I}^{\text{Decentralized}}}{I_{j,A}^{\text{Decentralized}}+I_{j,I}^{\text{Decentralized}}}=\frac{\left(\left(c_{j,A}\right)^{\frac{1}{\rho+1}}+\left(c_{j,I}\right)^{\frac{1}{\rho+1}}\right)^{\frac{\left(\rho+1\right)\left(1-\sigma\right)}{1+\rho\left(1-\sigma\right)}}}{\left(\left(c_{j,A}\right)^{\frac{1}{\rho+1}}+\left(c_{j,I}\right)^{\frac{1}{\rho+1}}\right)^{\frac{\left(\rho+1\right)\left(1-\sigma\right)}{1+\rho\left(1-\sigma\right)}}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 XXX Market gets correct the relative allocation some places, but not the
 levels.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Looking at equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: Downstream Objective"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: Upstream Objective"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we can see the elasticity of input costs with respect to upstream or downstrea
m input R&D is 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

.
 Since these firms additionally face the same costs, it follows that the
 input R&D should be equivalent between upstream and downstream sectors
 in a planned economy.
 However, when we move to the decentralized allocation, the private returns
 to input R&D will differ across stages.
 First, markups have two offsetting effects - higher markups lead to more
 R&D upstream, but also raise the input cost leading downstream firms to
 compensate with their own R&D.
 Second, we have the 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta-1$
\end_inset

 term, which is the elasticity of profits with respect to R&D, a similar
 R&D profit motive is absent in the planned economy.
 Finally, there is additionally over investment upstream due to a love-of-variet
y effect that is not internalized by any upstream firms.
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
XXX This might actually be because firms have to invest without knowing
 their shock.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
XXX Who to subsidize for spillovers.
 Bosch might have a production network that supports a lot of competitors,
 but it might also generate large local spillovers!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This suggests that downstream firms enjoy an environment with low variance
 in preference heterogeneity (i.e.
 high 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

).
 While we take the preference distribution as exogenous, one can imagine
 that if firms create increasingly homogenous downstream products or if
 entrants mimic existing products, then their preferences for inputs will
 become similar.
 This homogeneity in demand will lead to more excess upstream competition
 (relative to the preference of an industry planner), which moves the incidence
 of input R&D onto the balance sheet of suppliers.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
XXXFlesh our the role of 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 - then do the planner versus private changes w.r.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\end_inset

Finally, while we focus here on a homogenous firm model, it is worth noting
 that if there is heterogeneity in suppliers, there will be underinvestment
 by the lower cost suppliers.
 This is because while cost reductions achieved through R&D lead to higher
 demand, they lower the price received on those units of production.
 As for the industry planner, since any markup is just a transfer in profits
 between suppliers and buyers, the planner does not have this offsetting
 motive from lower prices.
 Note, we have a simplified model setup with fixed markups, if markups are
 higher for lower cost firms, then some of this underinvestment will be
 offset.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The market allocation is clearly not efficient, and this simplified model
 doesn't touch on other forces that would be present in a heterogenous firms
 model like business stealing or the input market expansion effects that
 might generate further wedges from the first-best.
 One obvious implication of this, there is room for policy to have first-order
 positive effects on welfare.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Sourcing Inputs from Abroad
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
XXX This affects 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{j,I}$
\end_inset

 too!! Need to adjust.
\end_layout

\end_inset

The first change we consider is a change in the price of foreign inputs
 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\text{Foreign}}$
\end_inset

 - perhaps spurred by tariff changes or a technology shock abroad.
 To implement this change, we write the input cost of downstream firms as
 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{-\theta}=(Mp_{f,j}^{-\theta}+p_{\text{Foreign}}^{-\theta})$
\end_inset

, where the model accounts for endogenous adjustments in 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{f,j}$
\end_inset

 but takes the foreign price as exogenous.
 We start by characterizing the effect on input prices
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d\log p_{f,j}=\frac{\frac{-2\rho}{1+2\rho\left(1-\theta\right)}\left(\theta+\frac{-\rho}{\rho+1}-\frac{1}{\rho+1}\lambda_{j}^{p_{j}^{F}}\right)\lambda_{\text{Foreign}}\left(d\log p_{\text{Foreign}}\right)}{1+\frac{2\rho}{1+2\rho\left(1-\theta\right)}\left(\theta+\frac{-\rho}{\rho+1}-\frac{1}{\rho+1}\lambda_{j}^{p_{j}^{F}}\right)\lambda_{\text{Home}}\left(1-\frac{1}{\theta}\frac{d\log M}{d\log p_{f,j}}\right)+\frac{2\omega}{1+2\rho\left(1-\theta\right)}\frac{d\log K}{d\log p_{f,j}}-\frac{2\rho}{1+2\rho\left(1-\theta\right)}\frac{d\log M}{d\log p_{f,j}}}
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\log p^{F}}{d\log p_{\text{Foreign}}}=\underbrace{\frac{d\log p_{f,j}}{d\log p_{\text{Foreign}}}}_{<0}\left(\lambda_{\text{Home}}\lambda_{j}^{p_{j}^{F}}\left(1-\frac{1}{\theta}\frac{d\log M}{d\log p_{f,j}}\right)-\omega\frac{d\log K}{d\log p_{f,j}}\right)+\lambda_{\text{Foreign}}\lambda_{j}^{p_{j}^{F}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop: Foreign Sourcing"

\end_inset

A change in the price of foreign inputs has an equilibrium effect on domestic
 input prices of
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(1-\eta_{a}\right)\frac{d\log p_{f,j}}{d\log p_{\text{Foreign}}}=\frac{-2\rho}{1+2\rho\left(1-\theta\right)}\left(\underbrace{\theta}_{\text{Competition}}+\underbrace{\frac{-\rho}{\rho+1}-\frac{1}{\rho+1}\lambda_{j}^{p_{j}^{F}}}_{\text{Expansion of Input Demand}}\right)\lambda_{\text{Foreign}}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{a}$
\end_inset

, defined in Appendix Equation X, summarizes the feedback effect of input
 prices on itself which includes the effects on quantities, entry, and the
 stock of local knowledge.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first direct effect of a change in the foreign input price is one of
 competition.
 Domestic suppliers now receive a smaller share of the total input demand
 and as a result face less incentive to innovate.
 At the same time, the decrease in input prices faced by downstream firms
 leads them to demand more inputs and adjusts their R&D expenditure away
 from inputs - freeing up more R&D to be done by suppliers.
 On balance, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta>1$
\end_inset

, the competition effect dominates, and tougher foreign competition leads
 to higher input prices.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
XXX Need to connect to literature on escape competition.
 How do you do this? Do you need to have firms intenalize effect on price
 index.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now to extrapolate to the effect on final prices, we need to account for
 a few more changes.
 Using Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem: Upstream Profits and Prices"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we note that alongside the change in input price, we have a change in
 the number of upstream entrants and a change in the stock of local knowledge.
 The change in the number of entrants of course has effects on the input
 price, contained in 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{a}$
\end_inset

, but they also have first-order effects in final prices through the love-of-var
iety effect and the effect of knowledge spillovers on the productivity of
 R&D by downstream firms.
 So, even if total expenditure on inputs falls, if foreign sourcing sufficiently
 deteriorates the amount of local R&D, then it can result in higher final
 prices.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d\log p^{F}}{d\log p_{\text{Foreign}}}=\underbrace{\frac{d\log p_{f,j}}{d\log p_{\text{Foreign}}}}_{<0}\left(\lambda_{\text{Home}}\lambda_{j}^{p_{j}^{F}}\left(1-\frac{1}{\theta}\underbrace{\frac{d\log M}{d\log p_{f,j}}}_{<0}\right)-\omega\underbrace{\frac{d\log K}{d\log p_{f,j}}}_{<0}\right)+\lambda_{\text{Foreign}}\lambda_{j}^{p_{j}^{F}}
\]

\end_inset

So if a downstream firm determined that foreign sourcing, while lowering
 input costs, could lead to ultimately worse local conditions, then what
 other strategies could it pursue? For one, it could set up a joint venture
 with the input supplier to move its R&D investment or knowledge from abroad
 into the local economy.
 This is perhaps what we are seeing in the partnerships between legacy automaker
s in the US and battery suppliers from China, Japan, and South Korea - joint
 ventures that seek to lower input prices but also transfer technology and
 know-how into the local economy.
 Additionally, note that we abstracted from endogenous adjustments abroad.
 A knock-on effect from foreign sourcing is that foreign suppliers will
 now undertake the input R&D previously done by local firms.
 Presumably those foreign firms transact more with foreign downstream competitor
s and share local knowledge spillovers with those firms.
 The reallocation of R&D abroad would then worsen the relative technological
 position of domestic firms.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, some caveats to these results.
 Note again that Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop: Foreign Sourcing"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 suggests that prices offered by domestic firms can only rise in response
 to foreign competition.
 We know that empirically, this isn't always the case (XXX reference), so
 here we offer three caveats to the model that allow foreign sourcing to
 lead to greater levels of innovation by domestic first.
 First, note that in a model with heterogeneous firms, the firms exiting
 would be the lowest productivity ones.
 This may lead to reallocation of demand such that remaining high productivity
 firms experience a rise in R&D.
 In light of Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop: Planner Solution"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, this reallocation corrects for underinvestment by high productivity firms.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Market Expansion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Second, the baseline model keeps the extent of the market for downstream
 goods fixed.
 But if this were not the case, if aggregate demand increased as prices
 fell, then foreign sourcing could lead to a more demand for all input suppliers.
 Suppose that the demand shifter satisfied 
\begin_inset Formula $D=\bar{D}P^{\sigma-1-\kappa}$
\end_inset

, then Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop: Foreign Sourcing"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 could be adjusted as follows: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\text{Expansion of Input Demand:}\quad\frac{-\rho}{\rho+1}-\frac{1}{\rho+1}\lambda_{j}^{p_{j}^{F}}\Rightarrow\frac{-\rho}{\rho+1}-\frac{1}{\rho+1}\frac{1+\kappa}{1-\kappa\rho}\lambda_{j}^{p_{j}^{F}}
\]

\end_inset

where if 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa$
\end_inset

 is sufficiently large, then the market expansion effect of foreign sourcing
 would lead to gains for even domestic suppliers.
