\begin_layout Subsection
Offshoring Assembly Abroad
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I next consider how offshoring assembly impacts input prices through the
 endogenous adjustment of R&D.
 While, we have abstracted from a discrete sense of geography in this industry
 equilibrium, we can approximate assembly offshoring through three changes.
 First there is a decrease in assembly costs, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{j,A}\downarrow$
\end_inset

, second an increase in the distance between downstream innovation and assembly
 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{j,A}$
\end_inset

, and third an increase in the distance between upstream innovation and
 downstream production 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{f,j}$
\end_inset

.
 The following proposition summarizes the first-order effects of these three
 changes on input prices.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop: Offshoring Assembly Equilibrium Response"

\end_inset

Offshoring assembly has an equilibrium effect on input prices of
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(1-\eta_{b}\right)d\log p_{f,j}=\frac{\tau}{1+2\rho}d\log d_{f,j}+\frac{2\rho}{1+2\rho}\frac{1}{\rho+1}\left(1-\lambda_{j}^{I}\right)\left(d\log c_{j,A}+\tau d\log d_{j,A}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{b}$
\end_inset

, defined in Appendix Equation X, summarizes the feedback effects of input
 prices on itself which includes the effects on quantities, spillovers,
 and entry.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A decrease in assembly costs or increase in assembly R&D efficiency (e.g.
 decrease in 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{j,A}$
\end_inset

) reduces prices and hence increases physical quantities.
 This raises the demand for inputs, captured by 
\begin_inset Formula $(1-\lambda_{j}^{I})/(1+\rho)$
\end_inset

, which in turn raises the R&D incentives of upstream firms and hence lowers
 prices (R&D response on prices is captured by 
\begin_inset Formula $2\rho/(1+2\rho)$
\end_inset

).
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The 
\begin_inset Formula $(1-\lambda_{j}^{I})/(1+\rho)$
\end_inset

 contains two forces - both the effect of lower prices on higher quantities
 - but also the lower assembly prices in particular leads to downstream
 R&D reallocation towards inputs, which dampens the quantity effect.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 A more direct effect is the effect of upstream R&D efficiency, i.e.
 the rise in 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{f,j}$
\end_inset

, which has a first-order effect on prices.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Two notes on Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop: Offshoring Assembly Equilibrium Response"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 First, it is not clear without estimate of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

 what the effect of offshoring is in input prices in a symmetric equilibrium
 - this is because 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{j,A}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{j,A}$
\end_inset

 move in opposite directions - offshoring offers better labor conditions
 for production but makes innovation harder due to the geographic fragmentation
 of production.
 Second, even if the effect of offshoring was to raise input prices, final
 prices might still fall.
 The determination follows from the following calculation: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d\log p^{F}=\left(1-\lambda_{j}^{I}\right)\left(d\log c_{A}+\tau d\log d_{j,A}\right)+d\log p_{f,j}\left(\lambda_{j}^{I}\left(1-\frac{1}{\theta}\frac{d\log M}{d\log p_{f,j}}\right)-\omega\frac{d\log K}{d\log p_{f,j}}\right)
\]

\end_inset

More concretely, changes in input prices will only alter final prices according
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{j}^{I}$
\end_inset

 - their share in final prices.
 If this share is small, or if the rise in input prices is insignificant,
 offshoring may still lower final prices.
 But, outside of the direct effect of an input price change, offshoring
 - if it raises input prices - will also lead to upstream exit and will
 lead to lower R&D investment by suppliers - deteriorating the spillover
 component of innovation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One caveat with this result, no firm uses the response in Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop: Offshoring Assembly Equilibrium Response"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 to calculate their returns to offshoring - this is purely the equilibrium
 effect where all firms experience the same change in fundamentals.
 To get some sense of the private incentives, we next consider the change
 in input prices faced by a particular infinitesimal firm when it alone
 offshores.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop: Offshoring Assembly Firm Response"

\end_inset

Consider offshoring by an infinitesimally small firm which poses no changes
 on prices indices or the aggregate demand faced by suppliers: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(1-\eta_{c}\right)d\log p_{f,j}=\frac{\tau}{1+\rho\left(1-\theta\right)}d\log d_{f,j}+\frac{\rho}{1+\rho\left(1-\theta\right)}\frac{\sigma}{1+\rho\left(1-\sigma\right)}\frac{1}{1+\rho}\left(1-\lambda_{j}^{p_{j}^{F}}\right)\left(d\log c_{j,A}+\tau d\log d_{j,A}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{c}$
\end_inset

, defined in Appendix Equation X, summarizes the feedback effects of input
 prices on itself which includes the effects on quantities, spillovers,
 and entry.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Or, consider a shock to assembly costs that occurs for some firms 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 but not 
\begin_inset Formula $-j$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have price difference, result from business stealling etc.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d\log p_{j}-d\log p_{-j}=\frac{\rho+1}{1+\rho\left(1-\sigma\right)}\left(\lambda_{A}d\log c_{j}^{A}+\lambda_{I}\frac{\rho}{1-\rho\left(\theta-1\right)}\frac{\sigma}{1+\rho\left(1-\sigma\right)}\frac{1}{1+\rho}\lambda^{A}d\log c_{j}^{A}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{2}$
\end_inset

, defined in Appendix Equation X, summarizes the recursive effect of input
 prices on itself which includes the effects on quantities, spillovers,
 and entry.
\end_layout

\end_inset

This expression offers several differences; to start, the 
\begin_inset Formula $2\rho/(1+2\rho)$
\end_inset

 is replaced by two terms.
 First, there is the fact that a firm that offshores has a lower relative
 price - hence higher demand.
 This is a business stealing effect - where the elasticity of substitution
 across downstream firms dictates the returns to offshoring.
 Second, there is the fact that when faced with greater demand from a particular
 buyer, upstream firms will invest more for that buyer, and extent of the
 investment response on the profit elasticity 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\left(\theta-1\right)$
\end_inset

.
 It is also clear from the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta>1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma>1$
\end_inset

, that the private returns from unilateral offshoring are larger than the
 equilibrium returns.
 Combined with fixed costs of offshoring, there is a possibility for a prisoner'
s dilemma to emerge.
 It may be privately optimal for any given firm to offshore from an equilibrium
 where all firms are on-shore, but the equilibrium achieved when all firms
 offshore leaves everyone worse off.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
So in equilibrium, profits aren't different - consumers face lowers prices
 - firms sunk costs for nothing.
 But, still individually profitable ex-ante if you give each firm the choice.
 Prisoners dilema.
\end_layout

\end_inset


