\begin_layout Standard
Finally, I unpack the term 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{b}$
\end_inset

, while there are subtle differences in 
\begin_inset Formula $\eta_{a},\eta_{b},\eta_{c}$
\end_inset

 - they all take the same general structure and capture the ways a change
 in input prices feedback on itself through equilibrium adjustments like
 entry, demand, and spillovers:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1-\eta_{b}\equiv1+\frac{2\rho}{1+2\rho}\left[\underbrace{\left(\frac{-\rho}{\rho+1}-\frac{1}{\rho+1}\lambda_{j,I}\right)}_{\text{Reallocation and Scale Effect on \ensuremath{\tilde{x}}}}\left[1-\underbrace{\frac{1}{\theta}\frac{d\log M}{d\log p_{f,j}}}_{\text{Love of Variety}}\right]\right]+\underbrace{\frac{2\omega}{1+2\rho}\frac{d\log K}{d\log p_{f,j}}}_{\text{Spillovers}}-\underbrace{\frac{2\rho}{1+2\rho}\frac{d\log M}{d\log p_{f,j}}}_{\text{Business Stealling}}
\]

\end_inset

Where recall that Lemma 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "lem: Upstream Profits and Prices"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 provides expressions for 
\begin_inset Formula $d\log M/d\log p_{f,j}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d\log K/d\log p_{f,j}$
\end_inset

 in terms of model parameters.
 As for intuition, we first have the downstream R&D reallocation and scale
 effects.
 Higher input prices lead to more downstream R&D on inputs, and less downstream
 quantities which both reduce the demand faced by upstream firms.
 Where note, the price faced by downstream firms for inputs consists of
 both the input price itself and the love of variety effect from the number
 of suppliers.
 Additionally, input prices affect entry and local R&D spillovers - with
 spillovers reducing prices by raising the efficiency of R&D and entry raising
 prices through a business stealing effect where each firm receives a lower
 share of demand and hence faces a lower return to cost reductions.
 
